{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_019GgkuGjnEhvBUYiq6JrDga","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the failure. Let me analyze what's happening:\n\nThe input file \"Faszerowana papryka.real.txt\" has:\n- Line 1: `Faszerowana papryka` (the correct title, mixed-case)\n- Line 2: `PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM` (ALL_CAPS, an alternate name)\n- Line 3: `파프리카 계란찜` (Korean text)\n- Line 4-5: Description text\n- Line 6: `NA 3 PAPRYKI` (metadata — filtered by METADATA_PATTERNS)\n\n\n- Line 7: `Przygotowanie` (section label)\n- Lines 8-9: Time metadata\n- Line 10: `SKŁADNIKI` (section label → \"SKLADNIKI\" in the set)\n- Lines 11-18: Ingredients\n- Lines 19-25: Instructions\n- Line 26: `WARZYWA` (a category label)\n\nThe expected output is `Faszerowana papryka` but the algorithm returns `WARZYWA`. Tracing through the logic, the first candidate at position 0 is mixed-case with 2 words, which should pass the initial filters.\n\nThe second candidate `PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM` at position 1 is all-caps with 2 words, and when I check the structural heading detection, both words have enough significant characters to qualify as a heading. The third candidate `WARZYWA` is all-caps but only a single word, so it fails the word count requirement.\n\nNow I'm moving into the bilingual detection logic... Since `PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM` shares no words with the Polish text, it's flagged as a translation and suppressed. Now I need to find the next structural heading to replace it, so I'm scanning through the remaining lines to identify which ones qualify as structural candidates.\n\nLooking at the metadata filtering, I'm checking whether \"10 minut\" matches the pattern for time durations — the regex looks for digits followed by \"MIN\" as a word boundary, but \"minut\" is a full word rather than an abbreviation, so I need to verify if it actually gets filtered. \"10 minut\" doesn't match the regex because \"min\" is followed by \"ut\", so it gets filtered out as starting with a number. For \"Pieczenie 30 minut\", the 'P' is uppercase so it's not garbled, but the \"30 minut\" substring still won't match the regex pattern since \"min\" isn't a complete word boundary. I'm checking whether \"Pieczenie 30 minut\" matches the metadata pattern for cooking times, but since \"Pieczenie\" is Polish and doesn't match the English keywords in the regex, it likely won't be filtered as metadata.\n\nMoving through the rest of the document, line 9 contains \"SKŁADNIKI\" which becomes \"SKLADNIKI\" after stripping diacritics and gets filtered as a section label, while lines 10-17 are the actual ingredients that pass through the ingredient filter.\n\nLine 18 starts with lowercase text so it's marked as garbled, and the remaining instruction lines get filtered similarly. Then I hit \"WARZYWA\" on line 25 — it's all caps and a single word, so it doesn't qualify as a structural heading, but since it's not in the section labels set and passes the hard filters, it could be treated as a candidate heading despite being a Polish word for vegetables.\n\nThe scoring becomes tricky here: \"WARZYWA\" gets the all-caps bonus of 0.08, but it's positioned at the very end of the document (relative position ≈ 1.0), which doesn't help its score since the position factor favors earlier content. I need to trace through what other structural headings exist and how the translation-flagging logic reassigns the first structural heading after the fixes. Without a structural heading bonus, `Faszerowana papryka` gets its score from the embedding match plus a position factor around 1.12, while `WARZYWA` gets a smaller embedding score but gains an all-caps bonus of 0.08 and a position factor of 1.0. The bilingual suppression filters out `PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM` as a translation candidate, then checks whether remaining candidates should be filtered based on whether they match any translation text...\n\nFiltering candidates against translations... I'm realizing the bilingual filter checks if the joined line \"Faszerowana papryka PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" contains \" paprika gyeran-jjim\" as a substring, which it does, so that combined entry gets suppressed. But the individual Polish entry \"Faszerowana papryka\" on its own doesn't match the filter pattern, so it should survive unless the caps-coalescing logic is merging consecutive all-caps lines under certain character limits first. The Korean text gets filtered out as garbled since it contains no Latin letters, so it doesn't make it into the candidates. For the multi-line join combining the Polish and romanized Korean entries, I need to check if that passes the hard filters too. Looking at the lowercase character count in \"papryka\" — it's 7 characters, well above the 2-character threshold, so it won't be flagged as garbled. The full joined line \"Faszerowana papryka PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" passes the section label check since it's not in the predefined labels, so it gets added to candidates. Now I'm checking the bilingual suppression logic where the lowercase version \"paprika gyeran-jjim\" is being compared.\n\nThe suppression check finds that this text appears in the full joined candidate, so that particular join gets filtered out. But the single-line \"Faszerowana papryka\" should still be in the scored candidates. The real question is why \"WARZYWA\" ends up with a higher threshold score than this single entry.\n\nLooking at the scoring, \"WARZYWA\" gets the all-caps bonus added to its raw score, while \"Faszerowana papryka\" doesn't. If the embedding model is somehow scoring \"WARZYWA\" higher despite it being just the word for vegetables, that would explain it. But I should check if there's another filtering mechanism at play—specifically the multi-title guard that filters selected results when multiple all-caps entries are present.\n\nChecking the multi-title guard logic... I'm checking the subheader logic—since WARZYWA is at the last line (position 25), there are no lines after it to check for ingredients, so it wouldn't qualify as a subheader. But if only WARZYWA is ALL_CAPS among the selected candidates, the logic picks whichever has the higher score, and WARZYWA likely wins due to the all-caps bonus combined with its position or raw score.\n\nThe real issue is that suppressing the bilingual translation candidate leaves WARZYWA as the sole ALL_CAPS option, which then triggers the single-candidate collapse and lets it win despite being just a category label rather than an actual recipe title.\n\nI can fix this by either adding category detection for words like WARZYWA, adjusting the multi-title guard logic to not always favor ALL_CAPS candidates, or weighting position more heavily since WARZYWA appears at the very end of the document.\n\nNow let me document the key patterns and write up the feedback. vegetables) is a recipe category/section marker at the end of the text, but it's not in the SECTION_LABELS set and thus passes hard filters. The ALL_CAPS bonus overrides positional bias — despite being at the last line, WARZYWA's capitalization advantage plus raw score benefits outweigh the actual title's embedding and position bonus. The multi-title guard that collapses to the highest scorer among mixed-case candidates backfires when that ALL_CAPS candidate is actually a category label rather than a title. Looking at the text structure, WARZYWA appears as a running footer or category label for a vegetables chapter section at the very end.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":14396,"cache_read_input_tokens":19613,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":14396},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8c7acb38-df3c-47e2-8c52-1f8dacd31ada","uuid":"ca0ca8ed-5c20-4e2b-bf19-8492b0161d86"}
